body_raw:
Let $S$ be a simply connected subset of $\mathbb{R}^2$ and let $x$ be an interior point of $S$ , meaning that $B_r(x)\subseteq S$ for some $r>0$ . Is it necessarily the case that $\pi_1(S\setminus\{x\})\cong\mathbb{Z}$ ? Let $B=B_r(x)$ and let $G=\pi_1(S\setminus\{x\})$ . I can show that $G^{ab}\cong\mathbb{Z}$ . Consider the commutative diagram of topological spaces $$ 
ewcommand{a}[1]{\kern-1.5ex\xrightarrow{\ \ #1\ \ }\phantom{}\kern-1.5ex} 
ewcommand{as}[1]{\kern-1.5ex\xrightarrow{\ \ \smash{#1}\ \ }\phantom{}\kern-1.5ex} 
ewcommand{\da}[1]{ igg\downarrowaise.5exlap{\scriptstyle#1}}  egin{array}{c}B\setminus\{x\}&a{}&S\setminus\{x\}&a{}&\mathbb{R}^2\setminus\{x\}\\da{}&&\da{}\B&a{}&S\end{array} $$ Applying the fundamental group functor gives a commutative diagram of groups $$  egin{array}{c}\mathbb{Z}&a{}&G&a{}&\mathbb{Z}\\da{}&&\da{}\1&a{}&1\end{array} $$ where the composition of the top two maps is the identity homomorphism on $\mathbb{Z}$ . By the Seifert-van Kampen theorem, the square is a pushout diagram of groups, meaning that the normal closure of the image of $\mathbb{Z}	o G$ is all of $G$ . In particular, if $A$ is an abelian group then any two homomorphisms $G	o A$ that agree on the image of $\mathbb{Z}	o G$ must agree on all of $G$ . Another way to put this is that if we have two homomorphisms $G	o A$ such that the two compositions $\mathbb{Z}	o G	o A$ are equal then the two homomorhpisms $G	o A$ are equal. I claim that the map $G	o\mathbb{Z}$ is an abelianization map. To see this, let $A$ be an abelian group and let $G	o A$ be a homomorphism. Now recall that the composition $\mathbb{Z}	o G	o\mathbb{Z}$ is the identity. Then the composition $\mathbb{Z}	o G	o\mathbb{Z}	o G	o A$ agrees with the composition $\mathbb{Z}	o G	o A$ . By the remark at the end of the previous paragraph, this means that the composition $G	o\mathbb{Z}	o G	o A$ agrees with the map $G	o A$ . In other words, the composition $\mathbb{Z}	o G	o A$ makes the abelianization diagram commute. To show uniqueness, let $\mathbb{Z}	o A$ be a map making the abelianization diagram commute. Then the composition $G	o\mathbb{Z}	o A$ agrees with the map $G	o A$ . Then the composition $\mathbb{Z}	o G	o\mathbb{Z}	o A$ agrees with the composition $\mathbb{Z}	o G	o A$ . Since the composition $\mathbb{Z}	o G	o\mathbb{Z}$ is the identity, this shows that the map $\mathbb{Z}	o A$ is given by the composition $\mathbb{Z}	o G	o A$ . This shows that the map $G	o\mathbb{Z}$ is an abelianization map.

